{
  "doc_id": "18547",
  "text": "We verified the role of ET-1 and hypoxia on the expression of metastatic SPARC. Hypoxia (administered as a gas mixture containing 5% CO 2 , 1% O 2 , and nitrogen balanced) was performed for 24 h [CITATION_1] . As shown in Figure 1B , in hypoxic 1833 cells, ET-1 transactivation and protein level consistently increased: The ET-1 luciferase activity was evaluated by a transient transfection for 24 h of the construct containing the 650-bp promoter fragment [CITATION_2] . Runx2 is a transcription factor involved in bone metabolism and tumor growth [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , and SPARC is a target gene of Runx2 [CITATION_6] , showing two HRE binding sites in the promoter. SPARC transactivation was downregulated under hypoxia, even if SPARC promoter does not present any HRE sequence. Thus, the effect of hypoxia on SPARCLuc seemed to be indirect, probably a consequence of Runx2 fall-down ( Figure 1C ). The dominant negative of the β subunit of HIF-1 (∆ARNT) further decreased Runx2 activity with respect to hypoxia alone, probably because HIF-1β is common to all members of the HIF-1 family [CITATION_7] . Based on our data (from Figure 1C ,D of the present paper and [CITATION_8] ), SPARC and Runx2 behaved similarly in response to different stimuli, and they were upregulated by ET-1 while being downregulated by hypoxia.",
